[[Image:Charles Dixon 1858-1926.png|thumb|right|Charles Dixon]] '''Charles Dixon''' (1858-17 June 1926) was an [[English people|English]] [[ornithology|ornithologist]], born in [[London]]. He discovered the [[St Kilda wren]] and a new species in North Africa. He collaborated with [[Henry Seebohm]] on his great work on ''British Birds'', in the second volume of which he summarized and modified [[Alfred Russel Wallace|A. R. Wallace's]] theory of the relation between nests and coloration of birds. Elliott Coues wrote in the preface to the American edition of Dixon's book "Rural bird life" pointing out the originality of the observations made from the field<ref>{{cite book |place=Boston|title=Rural bird life |author=Dixon, Charles| publisher=Estes and Lauriat| year=1880|url=https://archive.org/stream/ruralbirdlifebei00dixo#page/n13/mode/2up}}</ref> and [[Julian Huxley]] noted Dixon for recognizing the value of prismatic binoculars for bird study. In his later years, he wrote in the newspapers on agricultural fairs and horse shows.
==Biography==
Little is known of Dixon's early life. Dixon's early studies on ornithology were followed by numerous books. He did not believe in the role of [[natural selection]] in evolution and in his ''Evolution without Natural Selection'' (1885) he used examples of adaptations that were apparently of little survival value to illustrate his position. Reviewers were quick to point out that natural selection essentially works on adaptations that do have a survival value. He also argued that Darwin was mistaken to conclude that ornate male plumages evolved due to female selection.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Nature |volume=33|page=100|date=3 December 1885|doi=10.1038/033100a0| title=[Letters to the editor] “Evolution without Natural Selection”|author=Dixon, Charles}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.spectator.co.uk/article/29th-january-1898/8/curiosities-of-bird-life-by-charles-dixon-george-r|newspaper=The Spectator|date=29 January 1898|page=8|title=Curiosities of Bird Life. By Charles Dixon.|author=Anon.}}</ref>
Dixon made a special study of [[bird migration]] &mdash; especially in his 1892 book ''The Migration of Birds'' (new edition, 1897), an ingenious theoretical work &mdash; and of geographical distribution of birds. Dixon changed his ideas drastically between the two editions of his book on migration. In the 1892 edition he supported the idea that birds moved out of unfavourable environmental conditions but in the 1897 edition he suggested that migration is essentially derived from dispersal and range extension of birds.<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Journal of Biogeography| year=2008| volume=35| pages=1951–1959| author1=Bruderer, Bruno| author2=Salewski, Volker| title=Evolution of bird migration in a biogeographical context| doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2008.01992.x}}</ref> He believed that glaciation in former times could not have induced migration on its own and that southward migration was because of a former mass of tropical land that stretched around the equator. Reviewers did not think of his theories as being well-founded.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: Dixon's Migration of Birds |author=Allen, J.A.| journal=Auk| volume=15| issue=1| year=1898| pages=67–70|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v015n01/p0067-p0070.pdf| doi=10.2307/4068450}}</ref> Julian Huxley recognized him for noting the potential of prismatic binoculars to unravel the life of living birds.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v033n02/p0142-p0161.pdf|pages=142–161|author=Huxley, Julian|volume=33| issue=2|journal=The Auk|year=1916|title=Bird-watching and biological science|doi=10.2307/4072162}}</ref> He also published behavioural observations on birds and often incorporated these in his books.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Towering of Wounded Birds| author=Dixon, Charles| journal=Nature| volume=17| issue=420| page=45| year=1877| doi=10.1038/017045b0}}</ref> He recognized the threats to birds posed by human activity and was an early conservationist. He was quite opposed to the ideas of [[Acclimatisation society|acclimatisation]] and recognized the problem of introduction of species into Australia and New Zealand and their effects, especially on flightless birds.<ref>Lost and Vanishing Birds. p. 22.</ref> He expressed his conservation ethic thus:<ref>Lost and Vanishing Birds. p. 28.</ref>
{{quote|After all, we only hold the fauna of the world in trust, and it is but our bare duty to posterity to hand that fauna down as intact as we found it, or as nearly so as the reasonable exigencies of life will admit.}}
==Publications==
Of his many books, the following may be mentioned: * ''[https://archive.org/details/ruralbirdlifewi00dixogoog Rural Bird Life]'' (1880) * ''[https://archive.org/details/evolutionwithou00dixogoog Evolution without Natural Selection]'' (1885) * ''[https://archive.org/details/ourrarerbirdsbei00dixo Our Rarer Birds]'' (1888). * ''[https://archive.org/details/strayfeathersfro00dixorich Stray feathers from many birds: being leaves from a naturalist's note-book]'' (1890). * ''[https://archive.org/details/annalsofbirdlife00dixorich Annals of bird life : a year-book of British ornithology]'' (1890). * ''[https://archive.org/details/birdsofourramble00dixorich The Birds of our Rambles]'' (1891). * ''[https://archive.org/details/migrationofbirds00dixo The Migration of Birds] '' (1892). * ''[https://archive.org/details/jottingsaboutbir00dixorich Jottings about Birds]'' (1893). * ''[https://archive.org/details/nestseggsofbriti00dixorich The Nests and Eggs of British Birds]'' (1893; illustrated, 1894) * ''[https://archive.org/details/britishseabirds00dixorich British Sea Birds]'' (1896). * [https://archive.org/details/ourfavouritesong00dixo ''Our favourite song birds''] (1897) * ''Curiosities of bird life'' (1897)<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Pall Mall Gazette| date=22 October 1897|page=9|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000098/18971022/020/0009| via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]| subscription=yes| title=Reviews: Freaks of feathered creatures}}</ref> * ''[https://archive.org/details/lostvanishingbir00dixo Lost and Vanishing Birds]'' (1898). * ''[https://archive.org/details/gamebirdswildfow00dixorich Game Birds and Wild Fowl of the British Islands]'' (1899). * ''[https://archive.org/details/catalogueofcolleor00gall Bird-life in a Southern County]'' (1899). * ''[https://archive.org/details/storyofbirdsbein00dixorich The Story of the Birds]'' (1900). * ''[https://archive.org/details/amongbirdsinnort00dixo Among the birds in Northern Shires]'' (1900) * ''[https://archive.org/details/birdsnestsintrod00dixo Birds' Nests]'' (1902). * ''Open Air Studies in Bird Life: Sketches of British Birds in Their Haunts'' (1903). * ''[https://archive.org/details/birdlifeoflondon00dixo The Bird Life of London]'' (1909)
In later life he took an interest in agricultural and horse shows, especially the Richmond horse show. He died of a heart attack at his home in Harlesden in 1926.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000329/19260618/060/0005|title=Well-known journalist dead|page=5|newspaper=Western Morning News|date=18 June 1926|via=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> Seebohm named the [[long-tailed thrush]] ''Zoothera dixoni'' (originally in the genus ''Geocichla'').<ref name = "Jobling"> {{cite book | title = The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Names | first = James A. | last = Jobling | year = 2010 | location = London, UK | publisher = Christopher Helm | isbn = 978-1-4081-2501-4 | page = 138 }}</ref>
